{
  "texts": [
    "Introduction BackgroundConsumer-facing devices such as the Apple Watch [1] and Fitbit [2] now have the capability to notify users with a prediagnosis such as atrial fibrillation (AF).",
    "As these notifications may incentivize patients to seek follow-up medical care, wearables now have the potential to affect diagnosis rates and initiate cascades of medical care [3,4].",
    "Although these devices undergo premarket validation to obtain Food and Drug Administration (FDA) clearance [5], limited information exists on their postmarket use and clinical utility.To conduct postmarket surveillance on consumer wearables, electronic health records (EHRs) should capture wearable use, in particular those incidents where patients received prediagnosis notifications.",
    "However, EHRs are often built around medical diagnosis codes used for billing purposes [6,7], which do not contain terms for describing wearable use.",
    "Prescription wearables should have ordering information, but this does not capture how the wearables are used."
  ]
}